{{Communism sidebar|expanded=all}} Communist and Marxist ideologies generally allow state-provided [[abortion]], although there is no consensus among Communist parties and governments about how far into the pregnancy abortion should be allowed.
== Marxist Feminist views on abortion == Marxist feminists support the right of free access to abortion for women from all classes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.publicseminar.org/2016/06/feminisms-of-the-left-politics-and-strategy/|title=FEMINISMS OF THE LEFT: Politics and Strategy|work=Public Seminar|access-date=2018-08-30|language=en-US}}</ref>
== Communist parties views on abortion == In the Western world, the majority of the supporters of Communism also support abortion on request.
* The [[Communist Party USA]] supports the right of abortion and social services to provide access to it, arguing that unplanned pregnancy is prejudiced against poor women.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cpusa.org/interact_cpusa/what-is-the-cpusas-position-on-abortion/|title=What is the CPUSA's position on abortion rights?|first=Michelle|last=Kern|date=27 June 2016|website=Cpusa.org|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> * The [[Communist Party of Canada]] criticized Donald Trump's anti-abortion policies, including his defunding of the pro-choice organization [[Planned Parenthood]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://communist-party.ca/statement/2506|title=Unite to Stop the Right! " Communist Party of Canada - Parti Communiste du Canada|website=Communist-party.ca|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> * The [[Brazilian Communist Party]] supports abortion on request, criticizing relationships between state and religion leading to its ban.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pcb.org.br/portal2/20421/marcha-pela-legalizacao-do-aborto-na-america-latina/|title=Marcha pela Legalização do Aborto na América Latina|first=|last=admin|date=6 August 2018|website=Pcb.org.br|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>
== Marxist-Leninist countries == === People's Republic of China === The Chinese Penal Code does not criminalize abortion. Abortion is allowed until the 14th week of pregnancy, with abortions after the limit only permitted in special cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.womenonwaves.org/en/page/3184/china|title=China|first=Marc|last=Worrell|website=Women on Waves|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> Thoughts on abortions were influenced by the government's [[One-child policy]] and pressure from relatives, which led to a high number of sex-selective abortions and abortions after the legal time limit.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/womens-life/11858723/China-Forced-abortion-late-term-to-avoid-one-child-policy.html|title=Forcing a woman to have an abortion at eight months: Welcome to 21st century China|first=Yuan|last=Ren|date=11 September 2015|website=Telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> The human rights activist [[Chen Guangcheng]] was arrested for reporting cases of forced abortions in the Shandong province.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://internacional.estadao.com.br/blogs/claudia-trevisan/aborto-forcado-choca-a-china/|title=Aborto forçado choco a China|website=Internacional.estado.com.br|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>
To reduce the high number of sex-selective abortions, the Chinese government banned [[prenatal sex discernment]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/11/15/world/new-chinese-law-prohibits-sex-screening-of-fetuses.html|title=New Chinese Law Prohibits Sex-Screening of Fetuses|website=Nytimes.com|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>
=== Cuba === The Cuban government decriminalized abortion in 1965.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bélanger|first=Danièle|last2=Flynn|first2=Andrea|date=2009-01-01|title=The Persistence of Induced Abortion in Cuba: Exploring the Notion of an "Abortion Culture"|journal=Studies in Family Planning|volume=40|issue=1|pages=13–26|doi=10.1111/j.1728-4465.2009.00183.x|pmid=19397182|issn=0039-3665}}</ref> Late term abortions (those after 10 weeks), require a formal evaluation that is conducted by a committee of gynecologists and a psychologist.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bélanger|first=Danièle|last2=Flynn|first2=Andrea|date=2009-01-01|title=The Persistence of Induced Abortion in Cuba: Exploring the Notion of an "Abortion Culture"|journal=Studies in Family Planning|volume=40|issue=1|pages=13–26|doi=10.1111/j.1728-4465.2009.00183.x|pmid=19397182|issn=0039-3665}}</ref>
=== Vietnam === The Law of Protection of People's Health passed in 1989 states that: "Women have the right to have an abortion, to receive gynecological diagnosis and treatment, health check-up during pregnancy, and medical service when giving birth at health facilities."<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Abortion Policy|url=http://www.un.org/esa/population/publications/abortion/profiles.htm|journal=Viet Nam|volume=|pages=1|via=UN}}</ref>
Vietnam has also adopted policies to ban and prevent sex-selective abortion, among other countries such as Nepal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/study-debunks-myths-surrounding-sex-selective-abortion-bans-n161191|title=Study Debunks Myths Surrounding Sex-Selective Abortion Bans|website=Nbcnews.com|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>
=== Laos === Laos is the has the strictest limitations on legal abortions among current Marxist-Leninist countries; it is only allowed to save the life of the mother.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Abortion Policy|url=http://www.un.org/esa/population/publications/abortion/profiles.htm|journal=Lao People's Democratic Republic|volume=|pages=1|via=UN}}</ref>
== Former Marxist-Leninist == Many historical Marxist-Leninist countries, primarily in Europe, chose to allow abortion on request or due to socioeconomic factors. The Soviet Union under [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin]] and Romania under [[Nicolae Ceauşescu|Ceauşescu]], however, took action to further limit abortions, and other Communist countries retained prohibitive laws against them.
=== Soviet Union === During the Soviet regime in 1920, Russia legalized abortion, but in 1933, during the Stalinist era, views on it changed. In the Congress of Kiev in 1932, abortion was criticized for decreasing the country's birth rate. Abortion was finally banned in 1933. In her book, "[[Sexual Politics]]", the radical feminist [[Kate Millett]] criticized the Soviet regime for failing to support the social rights of women and homosexual people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://seminariolecturasfeministas.files.wordpress.com/2012/01/kate-millet-polc3adtica-sexual.pdf|format=PDF|author=Kate Millet|title=Politica Sexual|website=Seminariolecturasfeministas.files.wordpress.com|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> The number of officially recorded abortions dropped sharply from 1.9 million in 1935 to 570,000 in 1937, but began to climb just two years later, reaching 755,000 in 1939.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soviethistory.msu.edu/1936-2/abolition-of-legal-abortion/|title=Abolition of Legal Abortion|date=18 June 2015|website=Soviethistory.msu.edu|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> On November 23, 1955, the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, under [[Nikita Khrushchev]], legalized abortion. <ref>{{cite journal|title=The Re-Legalization of Abortion in Soviet Russia|first=Mark G.|last=Field|date=30 August 1956|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=255|issue=9|pages=421–427|doi=10.1056/nejm195608302550905|pmid = 13358858}}</ref>
=== Poland === Despite the protests of the Catholic Church, abortion in Poland was allowed on social grounds in 1956, and fully allowed in 1959 to protect the life and morality of women that had unsafe abortions. The abortions were provided by public hospitals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sxpolitics.org/frontlines/book/pdf/capitulo5_poland.pdf|format=PDF|title=The Struggle for Abortion Rights in Poland|website=Sxpolitics.org|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>
=== Hungary === Prior to 1953, abortion was only allowed to save the mother's life. In 1953 and 1956, the laws legalized abortion until 12 weeks of pregnancy, in cases of socioeconomic factors. In 1973, although abortion was still allowed for social reasons, the list of other acceptable reasons was reduced.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=mEyfOKHDORsC&pg=PA77&lpg=PA77&dq=ABORTION+HUNGARY+1953#v=onepage&q=ABORTION+HUNGARY+1953&f=false|title=Culture and Customs of Hungary|first1=Oksana|last1=Buranbaeva|first2=Vanja|last2=Mladineo|date=30 September 2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|accessdate=22 August 2018|via=Google Books|isbn=9780313383694}}</ref>
=== East Germany === In East Germany, women under 16 years of age, women over 40, and mothers with at least four children were given the right to abortion after applying to a state commission. Abortion was fully legalized by parliament in 1972.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1972/03/10/archives/east-german-parliament-approves-free-abortion.html|title=East German Parliament Approves Free Abortion|website=Nytimes.com|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>
=== Romania === Before 1966, Romania had the most liberal laws of abortion in Europe. However, after the rise of power of Nicolae Ceauşescu, [[Decree 770]] only allowed abortion to save the life of the mother. It was also allowed for women over 40 years old or with four or more children. In 1986, the age of tolerance was further raised to 45. The goal of the ban was a larger population that could drive a larger workforce and consumer-led growth, in order to achieve economic independence from the Soviet Union.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://searchinginhistory.blogspot.com/2014/01/decree-770-of-ceausescu.html|title=Decree 770 of Ceausescu - Searching in History|date=19 January 2014|website=Searchinghistory.blogspot.com|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> Over the span of these 23 years, more than 2 million unwanted children, were born and at least 10,000 women died as a result. The 770 Decree was one of the first laws to be repealed right after Ceauşescu's trial and execution on the 25th of December, 1989; more than 1 million abortions were performed the year after, more than three times the number of children born that year.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}
=== Czechoslovakia === An abortion law passed in 1957 allowed termination for, both medical (forming 10% of the cases) and other reasons (the remaining 90%).<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/article-abstract/659293|title=Legal Abortion in Czechoslovakia|first=Věra|last=Kőlblová|date=25 April 1966|journal=JAMA: The Journal of the American Medical Association|volume=196|issue=4|page=371|accessdate=24 August 2018|doi=10.1001/jama.1966.03100170113043}}</ref> The law was changed after 1957.{{clarify|reason=how it was changed|date=September 2018}} The birth ratio decreased, falling below number of abortions. <ref>{{cite journal|title=Legalized abortion in Czechoslovakia|first1=J.|last1=Zidovsky|first2=A.|last2=Zwinger|date=24 August 1972|journal=Medical Gynaecology, Andrology, and Sociology|volume=8|issue=2|pages=7–9|pmid=12256872}}</ref>
=== Bulgaria === Abortion was legalized on April 27, 1956. It was only allowed once every 6 months, and no later than the 12th week of pregnancy except for health reasons. To increase the birth rate, the government restricted abortion for certain women in February 1968 by the Decree 188, which discouraged childless women and women with one or two children from having an abortion (although they could possibly have the procedure if they persisted). Only women with three or more children, or women over 45 years ago, had the right to an abortion on request. The time ceiling was also lowered to 10 weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.un.org/esa/population/publications/abortion/doc/bulgaria1.doc |title=Data |website=www.un.org}}</ref> In April 1973, women with just one child lost the right to abortion except in cases of rape, incest, medical emergency, if the woman was an unmarried person under the age of 18 with no living children, or if she was over 45 years old with a living child. By 1974, unmarried women were allowed to get an abortion.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}
=== Yugoslavia === Abortion was legalized in 1952.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.znajznanje.org/abortion-rights-in-the-former-ex-yugoslavia-abortion-as-a-human-right/|title=// Abortion rights in the former ex-Yugoslavia: abortion as a human right – znajznanje.org|website=Znajznanje.org|accessdate=24 August 2018}}</ref> Article 191 of the federal constitution states that "it is a human right to decide on the birth of children". All the republics of Yugoslavia passed laws between 1977 and 1979 that regulated abortion; in Croatia, for example, abortion was only allowed until 10 weeks of pregnancy, but in Slovenia it was allowed after the 10 weeks on request.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}
=== Albania === During [[Enver Hoxha|Enver Hoxha's]] rule, abortion was only legally allowed to save mother's life,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/albanian-women-remember-fear-of-abortion-during-communism-11-06-2017|title=Albanian Women Remember Fear of Abortion During Communism|website=Balkaninsight.com|accessdate=24 August 2018}}</ref> but in practice could be obtained for any reason. The punishment for a woman who had an abortion was social reprimand by re-education through work. By 1989, abortion was officially legalized in cases of rape, incest, and for women under 16 years old, among other reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.un.org/esa/population/publications/abortion/doc/albani1.doc |title=Data |website=www.un.org}}</ref>
=== North Korea === The Penal Code from 1950 states that abortion is allowed for "important reasons" up to the seventh weeks of pregnancy, but that anyone who performs an abortion for no important reason is subject to up to three years' imprisonment. The lack of specification of "important reasons", though, has increased leeway for abortions on request.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.womenonwaves.org/en/page/4290/north-korea|title=North Korea|first=Marc|last=Worrell|website=Women on Waves|accessdate=24 August 2018}}</ref>
=== Mongolia === Induced abortion in socialist Mongolia was allowed since 1940 to preserve the mother's health, officially recorded in the penal code on July 6, 1960.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.un.org/esa/population/publications/abortion/doc/mongolia.doc |title=Data |website=www.un.org}}</ref> In 1986, the amendment authorized medical authorities to decide when to perform an abortion, and abortion was fully legalized in 1989.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}
=== Kampuchea === According to the French penal code, abortion in Kampuchea was prohibited, but the general criminal law principles of necessity allowed abortion to save mother's life. Due the period of extended turmoil during the Communist Regime, the laws about abortion then were unclear, and untrained health workers accepted requests for abortions.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}
=== Afghanistan === The criminal code from 7 October 1976 only allowed abortion to save the mother's life. The socialist government never changed this law. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.un.org/esa/population/publications/abortion/doc/afghan1.doc |title=Data |website= |publisher=www.un.org}}</ref>
=== South Yemen === The law of South Yemen only allowed abortion to save the mother's life, as with North Yemen. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.un.org/esa/population/publications/abortion/doc/yemen.doc |title=Data |website=www.un.org}}</ref>
=== Angola === Abortion remained prohibited in Angola, and was only allowed in order to save the mother's life.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Abortion Policy|url=http://www.un.org/esa/population/publications/abortion/profiles.htm|journal=Angola|volume=|pages=1|via=UN}}</ref> === Mozambique === Before 1981, abortion was only allowed to save the mother's life. In 1981, abortion was allowed in case of contraceptive failure. Since then, the law has been interpreted very liberally in some hospitals, leading them to accept women who sign a written statement requesting the abortion.<ref>[https://laubeyrietechnology.com/c.php?cu=https%253A%252F%252Fr.search.yahoo.com%252Fcbclk%252FdWU9QjhDMUQ4NDZGNzcxNERBNSZ1dD0xNTM0OTg1NzY5MTgzJnVvPTcxMjYyMTM0Mjk2MzUyJmx0PTImZXM9UjYwQ09qd0dQUzljei5EVA--%252FRV%253D2%252FRE%253D1535014569%252FRO%253D10%252FRU%253Dhttps%25253a%25252f%25252fwww.bing.com%25252faclick%25253fld%25253dd36V2S9K9o3X4alvWPetevQTVUCUx51YoMctjLp2qjZgA0CnEbs5FQ4CsOK-7uuLuhJEMwaTCWpgPNdkBbu39qxsd8tiFLG5PF3Djw8TbuHUG91UG5R0YPGc5vUkXewcp4JeZV-TBAlibqei43nWXnwR00wMI%252526u%25253dhttps%2525253a%2525252f%2525252fwww.ibyte.com.br%2525252f%2525253futm_source%2525253dbingads%25252526utm_medium%2525253drededepesquisa%25252526utm_campaign%2525253dferias%252525252Btecnologia%25252526utm_term%2525253drededepesquisabinginstitucional%25252526utm_content%2525253djulho2018%25252526msclkid%2525253d%2525257bmsclkid%2525257d%252FRK%253D2%252FRS%253D7WwhoCRJGtngCCb93OHKkldB3V0-&sh=www.ibyte.com.br&l=BR&po=1&u=52345X0000XZZZZZZZZZZZZZZZZZZZZZ&a=3453&tr=5b7e062884cd4&keyword=tv+led&aid=5b7e06295fb8f&b=&uc=BR&ut=52345X0000XZZZZZZZZZZZZZZZZZZZZZ&rt=1534985769.3904&bc=1&e7d42=1&t=1&tbm=&loc=pu ]{{dead link|date=August 2018}}</ref>
=== Benin === The civil code from 8 February 1973 only allowed abortion to save the mother's life, which the socialist government never changed.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}
=== People's Republic of the Congo === Abortion was prohibited, but the general principles of criminal law allowed abortions on grounds of medical necessity, with reports suggesting they were also permitted for less immediately dangerous complications.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}
=== Ethiopia === Abortion was only allowed to “save the pregnant woman from the grave and permanent danger to life or health that is impossible to avert in any other way”. Although the code does not accept broad health, judicial or socio-economic grounds, and doesn't specify whether a threat to health includes both physical and mental health, it does consider a “grave state of physical or mental distress, especially following rape or incest, or because of extreme poverty” a mitigating circumstance in sentencing.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}
=== Somalia === Since December 16, 1962, abortion was prohibited. The socialist regime never changed the law, but the criminal law's general principles of necessity allowed for an abortion to save the mother's life.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}
=== Madagascar === Abortion was prohibited in Madagascar and only allowed to save the mother's life.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}
=== Grenada === There is no information about the abortion status under the short-lived Grenada socialist government. The current legislation allows abortion to preserve the mother's health.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ceped.org/cdrom/avortement_ameriquelatine_2007/en/chapitre1/page3.html|title=Abortion in Latin America and the Caribbean|website=Ceped.org|accessdate=24 August 2018}}</ref>
== Other Communist areas ==
=== Democratic Federation of Northern Syria === Although Syria only allows abortion to save a mother's life, the [[de facto]] [[autonomous region]] of the DFNS legalizes abortion for all women. Barbara Anna, a member of the Turkish Communist Party, reflected more broadly on how limits to women’s bodily autonomy relate to the imposition of capitalism and imperialism. She compared the situations in the Middle East where women’s economic activity and sexual freedom is heavily restricted to the situation in the neoliberal capitalist centre, where women’s sexual freedom comes at the expense of constant objectification and commodification.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lookleftonline.org/2018/05/kurdish-women-call-for-yes-vote/|title=Kurdish women call for YES vote|website=LookLeft|accessdate=24 August 2018}}</ref>
=== Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia === The [[Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia]] supported abortion, despite the laws of Colombia only allowing it in cases of rape, fetal defects, or a need to preserve the mother's health.<ref name="bbc.com">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/portuguese/noticias/2003/030310_colombiaguerrilheirasvr.shtml|title=Farc têm grande contingente de mulheres guerrilheiras - BBC Brasil - BBC World Service|website=Bbc.com|accessdate=24 August 2018}}</ref>
=== Paris Commune === Article XII states that "The submission of the children and the mother to the authority of the father, who prepares the submission of each one to the authority of the chief, is pronounced dead. The couple consents freely to seek common pleasure. The Commune proclaims freedom of birth: the right to sexual information from childhood, the right to abortion, the right to contraception. As the products cease to be the property of their parents. They live together in their home and run their own lives." This was in sharp contrast to the French law at the time, which prohibited abortion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://psolufmg.blogspot.com/p/ha-140-anos-comuna-de-paris.html|title=Núcleo Psol UFMG: Decretos da Comuna de Paris de 1871|website=Psolufmg.blogspot.com|accessdate=24 August 2018}}</ref>
