{{refimprove|date=January 2014}} {{Fascism sidebar}}
'''Crypto-fascism''' is the secret support for, or admiration of, [[fascism]]. The term is used to imply that an individual or group keeps this support or admiration hidden to avoid [[political persecution]] or [[political suicide]]. The common usage is "crypto-fascist", one who practices this support.
The term is sometimes credited{{citation needed|date=September 2017}} to [[Gore Vidal#Politics|Gore Vidal]], though the [[Oxford English Dictionary]] cites several earlier uses, including ''[[The Guardian]]'' using the term more than once in the 1920s. In an [[ABC Television|ABC]] television debate during the chaos of the [[1968 Democratic National Convention]], Vidal described [[William F. Buckley, Jr.]] as a "crypto-[[Nazism|Nazi]]", later correcting himself as meaning to say "crypto-fascist". However, the term had appeared five years earlier in a German-language book by the sociologist [[Theodor W. Adorno]], ''Der getreue Korrepetitor'' (The Faithful Répétiteur).<ref>Adorno, ''Gesammelte Schriften'', vol.&nbsp;15, p.&nbsp;191.</ref>
The term was famously used by German Nobel laureate [[Heinrich Böll]] in a 1972 essay (titled "{{Interlanguage link multi|Will Ulrike Gnade oder freies Geleit?|de}}")<ref name=spiegelboell>{{cite web |url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-43019376.html |title=Will Ulrike Gnade oder freies Geleit? Schriftsteller Heinrich Böll über die Baader-Meinhof-Gruppe und "Bild" |last1=Böll |first1=Heinrich |date=1972-01-10 |publisher=[[Der Spiegel]] |access-date=2016-02-03 |language=German}}</ref> that was sharply critical of the tabloid newspaper [[Bild]]'s coverage of the [[Baader-Meinhof Gang]] left-wing terrorist organization. In the essay, Böll stated that what ''Bild'' does "isn’t cryptofascist anymore, not fascistoid, but naked fascism. Agitation, lies, dirt."<ref name=spiegelboell/>
