{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}
{{Use Australian English|date=August 2016}}
The '''Majority Labor Party''', sometimes called the '''Majority Australian Labor Party''', was an [[Australia]]n political party formed by federal [[Australian Labor Party]] MP [[James Catts]] in 1922. It did not win any seats in parliament.

Catts resigned from the Labor Party in 1922, blaming the loss of the 1922 state election on [[Irish people|Irish]]ism, [[Bolshevism]] and [[Tammany Hall|Tammanyism]] within the party. It was also associated with the recently elected state member for [[Electoral district of Newcastle|Newcastle]], [[Walter Skelton]], and his [[Protestant Labor Party]]. The party contested the [[Australian federal election, 1922|1922 federal election]], but with little success, and ceased to exist shortly afterwards.<ref>[http://toilereditions.com.au/asslh.org.au_The%20Protestant%20Indpendent%20Labour%20Party%20Of%20NSW,%201923-1929_files/splash_data/about.htm The Protestant Independent Labor Party of NSW, 1923-1929]</ref>{{dead link|date=August 2016}}

